commit.message: Fix import warnings on Python3

setup: include LICENSE in MANIFEST.in (fixes #39)

Rather than using data_files.
readme: add note about twine
setup: bump version
Portably require enum34 for python < 3.4

Require enum34 only for python<3.4

As suggested for this exact use case here:
https://stackoverflow.com/a/32643122/4935114

Fix #27: Add license file to dist package

Signed-off-by: Nick Diego Yamane <nick@diegoyam.com>

tokenizer: remove unused COND_ERROR (fixes #20)

This fixes https://github.com/idank/bashlex/issues/20, as can be shown
by comparing the output of the following command before/after this
change:

    rm bashlex/parsetab.py*; make tests

travis: test python 3.6 as well as 2.7.12 and 3.5

Here are the Python 3.6.0 release notes:
https://www.python.org/downloads/release/python-360/
setup: bump version

readme: add travis badge

See https://docs.travis-ci.com/user/status-images/

parser: fix 'hack' table to derive states dynamically (fixes #7)

the states which need fixing by the 'hack' are different for different Python
versions and even differ on Windows vs Linux. Derive them dynamically
from the state 0, this makes the test suite pass on Python 3.

bashlex: add python 3 support

* __nonzero__ in Py3 is __bool__
* range returns an iterator instead of a list in Py3
* made imports more specific
* setuptools have different imports in Py2 and Py3
Makefile: don't try to run tests if nose is missing

Makefile: run nose through python, not directly

This makes it easier to run the tests against multiple versions of
Python installed using a version manager like pyenv.

References:
https://askubuntu.com/questions/588390/how-do-i-check-whether-a-module-is-installed-or-not-in-python/588392#588392
https://github.com/nose-devs/nose/pull/635
https://github.com/yyuu/pyenv

Makefile: actually redirect stderr to /dev/null

See https://unix.stackexchange.com/questions/80629/redirect-both-stderr-and-stdout-to-dev-null-with-bin-sh/80632#80632

travis: add basic config for python 2, 3.5

See https://docs.travis-ci.com/user/languages/python/
tokenizer: don't crash on empty input

parser: move split() from tokenizer, pass parser to subst._expandwordinternal (fixes #12)

I broke this in 4e091dd and probably hadn't noticed because I didn't run the
doctests. Add a Makefile with a test target so I never forget.

split() returns a generator, not a list
